Task 5: Process Management & Monitoring
🕵️‍♂️ Monitoring and Controlling System Resources
DevOps Engineer: Sumbul Zahra 🚀

Project Overview
A DevOps Engineer must ensure that applications are running smoothly. 
If a process consumes too much CPU or hangs, we need the skills to identify it (PID) and terminate it safely.
In this task, I managed background processes and monitored system health in real-time.

Step-by-Step Implementation
Starting a Background Process
I initiated a long-running process and redirected the output so it wouldn't clutter the terminal.

Bash
ping google.com > ping_test.log &
The & at the end sends the process to the background.

Monitoring the Process
I used three different tools to observe the system:

ps aux: A snapshot of all running processes.

top: A dynamic, real-time view of system resources.

htop: An interactive and more visual process viewer.

Terminating the Process
First, I found the Process ID (PID) using grep, then I stopped it.

Bash
ps aux | grep ping
# Locate the PID from the output
kill <PID_NUMBER>
Final Verification
Ensuring the process is no longer active:

Bash
ps aux | grep ping
Key Commands Learned
top / htop: Real-time system monitoring.

ps aux: Listing all active processes.

kill: Terminating a process by its ID.

jobs: Viewing tasks running in the current shell session.

